window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>1","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : CONCEPT OF ENERGY","question":"In a collision between two object, Kinetic energy is conserve only if .","images":[],"options":{"A":"One of the objects was initially at rest","B":"Potential energy is converted to work","C":"The collision is inelastic","D":"The collision is elastic"},"answer":"D","explanation":"There are two types of collision   -Elastic colision   -inelasic collision  In elastic colision both the linear momentum and kenetic energy are conserved  In inelastic collision, linear momentum is conserved but kinetic energy is not conserve . this implies that there is loss of kinetic energy when the collision is inelastic.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>2","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : TYPES OF MOTION","question":"The quantity of motion of a body is its","images":[],"options":{"A":"Acceleration","B":"Displacement","C":"momentum","D":"Velocity"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The quantity of motion of a body is a measure of mass and velocity of the body . This is the product of the ass of a body and its velocity , which is the momentum of the body. Mathematically, linear momentum , p = mass(m) x veocity   p = mv","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>3","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"The volume of a fixed mass of a gas varies inversely as the pressure on it provided the temperature is constant. This statement is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Pressure law","B":"Charles law","C":"Boyle's law","D":"General gas law"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Boyle's law states that the volume of a fixed mass of gas is inversely proportional to pressure provided temperature is constant.  Mathematically,  V \u221d 1/p   v = k/p  where k is a constant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>4","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"An image formed on a screen is always.","images":[],"options":{"A":"Inverted","B":"magnified","C":"upright","D":"virtual"},"answer":"A","explanation":"There are two types of images : real and virtual . A real image is the image which can be cast on a screen . it is formed when the light rays coming from an object actually meet after reflection. It is always inverted , an example is the image formed on the cinema screen. on the other hand a virtual image is an image which cannot be cast on a screen , the rays of light forming a virtual image do not actually meet where the image is formed . Virtual image is always upright or erect","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>5","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"How would the capacitance of a parallel plate capacitor be affected if the distance of separation of its plates is decreased? it will","images":[],"options":{"A":"increase in value","B":"decrease slightly","C":"Remain unchanged","D":"drop to Zero"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The factors affecting the capacitance of a capacitor are :  - Nature of the di-electric  - Area of the plates of the capacitor  - Distance between he plates of the capacitor . they are related by the formular,  C=EAd  Where C = Capacitance ,E = Absolute permitivity, A = Area of the plates , d = Distance between he plates . it can be seen that capacitance is inversely proportional to the distance between the plates . Decrease in the distance between the plates results in to increase in capacitance and vice versa.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>6","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"MACHINES :","question":"Which of the following machines does not apply the lever principle ?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Claw hammer","B":"wheelbarrow","C":"single pulley","D":"sugar tong"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A lever is a simple achine that is comprised of a rigid beam which is fixed on a pivot. It consists of three parts which are load , fulcrum and effort. It fulcrum is at the middle , it is a first class lever e.g Claw hammer , if the load is at the midddleit is a second class lever e.g wheel barrow . if the effort is at the middle , it is a third class lever e.g sugar tong. A pulley is another type of machine which is not  lever . A pulley is a whell which has a rope around it , hence it does not apply the lever principle.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>7","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"The average distance moved by a molecules between collision is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"Molecular distance","B":"intermolecular distance","C":"Mean distance","D":"Mean free path"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Mean free path is the average distance travelled by a moving molecules between collision . It is the actual distance a particle such as a molecule in a gas moves before a collision","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>8","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF MECHANICAL WAVES","question":"Which of the following waves requires a material medium for its propagation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Radio waves","B":"Light waves","C":"sound wave","D":"X-rays"},"answer":"C","explanation":"There are two types of waves :  - mecanical waves - these are waves which require material medium for their propagation e.g sound waves, water waves.  - Electromagnetic wave : Theses are waves which do not require material medium for their propagation e.g Radiowaves , light , X-rays e.t.c.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>9","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CONDUCTION THROUGH MATERIALS","question":"The depolarizing agent in a leclanche cell is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Carbon rod","B":"ammonia Chloride","C":"manganse(IV) oxide","D":"Zinc plate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A lechlanche cell is a primary cell, this means that it cannot be recharged after it has been used up. it has a positive electrode (cathode) is carbon, it negative electrode (anode) is zinc, it has an electrolyte which is ammonium chloride (NH4Cl) and depolarizer which maganese(iv) oxide (MnO2).","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>10","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"The material used to slow down the neutron in a nuclear reactor is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Boron","B":"Copper","C":"Graphite","D":"Uranium"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Newton moderation are material used in a nuclear reactor to slow neutron down , such moderator are graphite , beryllum e.t.c they help reduce speed of neutron  which could cause further fission","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>11","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : EFFECTS OF HEAT ON MATTER","question":"Which of the following statement explains why soapy water is more effective in cleaning oil-stained dishes","images":[],"options":{"A":"The oil on the dishes repels the soap","B":"Soap and heat decrease the surface tension of the water","C":"Hot water increases the surface tension","D":"Soap increases the surface tension of oil and water"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Some of the ways of reducing surfae tension are boiling , adding saop or detergent , by adding camphor , by adding grease. Ordinary water is not so effective in cleabibg oil stained dishes due to the presence of surface tension but whe hot soapy water is used , washing is more effective since surface tension has been greately reduced.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>12","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"The diagram above illustrates a beam of parallel rays from a distance object O, incident on one side of the total refecting prism.  Which diagram does not represent the correct path of the beam when it emerges from the prism?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"W","B":"X","C":"Y","D":"Z"},"answer":"A","explanation":"When drawing ray diagram for instance drawing two ray from head of the object , the point pf intersection of the two rays represents the position of the head of the image , but in a case of parallel rays of light drawn from the object such that the image is likewise formed at infinity , the ray from t head of the object forms the head of the image , similarly, the ray from the leg of the image . from the diagrams drawn , it is only in  W that the ray from the head forms the leg of the image , others are correctly drawn.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>13","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"An electric device has 50 turns in its primary coil and 20 turns in the secondary coil.The device can be a/an","images":[],"options":{"A":"Step-up transformer","B":"Step-down transformer","C":"Dc generator","D":"a.c generator"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the number of turns of coil in the secondary coil is greater than that of the primary coil , it is a step-up transformer but when the turns in the secondary coil is less than tthat of the primary coil it is a step-down transformer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>14","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : TRANSMISSION OF SOUND WAVES","question":"The earpiece of a telephone handset converts energy from","images":[],"options":{"A":"Electrical to sound","B":"sound to electrical","C":"Radio wave to sound","D":"Sound to radio wave"},"answer":"A","explanation":"There wire of the earpiece takes the electrical energy from the headset which is then converted to sound energy by the earpiece.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>15","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"The identical cups containing the same volume of water at 45\u2218C and 5\u2218C are left in a room a 25\u2218C. which of the following graphs correctly illustrates the variation of temperatures with time?","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"C","explanation":"The cup containing water at 45\u2218C loses heat to the room since temperature of the room is lower than its temperature , hence it temperature reduces gradually , the cup containing water at 5\u2218C gains heat from the room since its temperature is lower than that of the room. hence, its temperature increases gradually , the lines are curved because as the temperature of the water changes the temperature difference between th water and surrounding also changes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>16","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light travelling from glass into ethyl alcohol is incident at the boundary at an angle of incidence 30\u2218. calculate the angle of refraction.[Refractive index of glass =1.5; refractive index of ethyl alcohol = 1.36]","images":[],"options":{"A":"27.0\u2218","B":"33.5\u2218","C":"51.7\u2218","D":"2.8\u2218"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Angle of incidence l = 30\u2218  Angle of refraction , r = ?  Refractive index of glas ng = 1.5  Refractive index of ehyl alcohol, ne = 1.36  from snel' law :  neng=sinisinr  1.361.5=sin30sinr  1.3sinr = 1.5sin30  sinr=1.5sin301.36  Sinr=1.5x0.51.36  Sin r = 0.5515   r = sin-10.5515  r = 33.5\u2218","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>17","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"NEWTON\u2019S LAWS OF MOTION : SECOND LAW","question":"A 60kg man stands on the weighing balance in an elevator accelerates upwards at 5mg-2. determine the reading of the scale [g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"options":{"A":"300N","B":"600N","C":"800N","D":"900N"},"answer":"D","explanation":"mass, m = 60kg  g = 10ms-1  acceleration , a = 5ms-2  From an elevated accelerating upward, the reading of the scale , R = m (g+a)   = 60 (10+5)   = 60 x 15  R = 900N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>18","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : THERMAL EXPANSION","question":"The length of an iron bar is 100 cm at 20\u2218C. At what temperature will its length increase by 0.01% ?[Linear expansivity of iron = 1.2 x 10-5 = C-1]","images":[],"options":{"A":"48.0\u2218C","B":"38.0\u2218C","C":"28.3\u2218C","D":"23.0\u2218C"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Lenght l1 = 100cm  initial temp.\u03b8  =  20\u2218C  Finall temperature,\u03b82 = ?  Change in lenght , \u2206l = 0.01%   =0.01100x100   = 0.01cm  Final lenght , l2 = 100+0.01  = 100.01cm  Linear expansitivity   \u221d = 1.2 x 10-5 C-1  Recall,\u221d=\u2206ll\u2206\u03b8  1.2x10-5=0.01100\u2206\u03b8  1.2 x 10-5 x 100\u2206\u03b8 = 0.01  \u2206\u03b8=0.011.2 x 10-5 x 100  \u2206\u03b8 = 8.3\u2218C  Final temperature ,\u03b82 = 20+8.3 = 28.3\u2218C","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>19","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CIRCUIT","question":"A moving-coil galvanometer which gives a full-scale deflection with 0.005 it is converted to a voltmeter , reading up to 5F\u2218 using an estimated resistance of 975\u03a9","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.25\u03a9","B":"2.50\u03a9","C":"25.00\u03a9","D":"250.00\u03a9"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For a galvanometer to be converted to a voltmeter, a resistor of high rsistance (multiplier ) must be connected in series with it.    IG = 0.005A is te current that passes through the resistor and the galvanometer   V2 = Voltage across the external resistor  VG = Voltage across the galvanometer   V = VR + VG  V = IGR + IGR  5 = 0.005 x 975 + 0.005RG  5 = 4.875 + 0.005RG  5 = 4.874 = 0.005RG  0.125 = 0.005RG  0.1250.005=RG  RG = 25.00\u03a9","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>20","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE NUCLEUS : COMPOSITION OF THE NUCLEUS","question":"A beam consisting of \u03b1 particles, \u03b2-particles and y-rays pass through a magnetic field at right angles to the direction of the field. Which of the following observation would be made about the \u03b1-particles, \u03b2-particles and y-rays respectively?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Deflected, deflected,deflected","B":"deflected,deflected, not deflected","C":"deflected, not deflected, deflected","D":"Not deflected,deflected,deflected"},"answer":"B","explanation":"\u03b1 - Particles are reresented by helium nuceus and they are positviely charged   \u03b2 - articls are streams of eectrons which are negatively charged   y  - rays are not particles and they do not posses any charge. they are neutral in nature  Therefore , \u03b1-particles and \u03b2-particles are deflected while y-rays are not deflected when passed through a magnetic field.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>21","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CAPACITANCE, ARRANGEMENT AND APPLICATION","question":"A parallel plate capacitor is charged and the charging battery subsequently disconnected. If the plates of the capacitor are moved farther apart by means of insulating handle, the","images":[],"options":{"A":"Capacitance would increase","B":"capacitance would decrease","C":"charge on the capacitor would increase","D":"charge on the capacitor would decrease"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When the capcitor is charged and disconnected , the charge stored on the plates remain the same, even when the plates are seperated . But the capacitor is inversely proportional to the distance between the plates. Hence when the distance between the plates increase, capacitance decrease.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>22","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SPEED OF SOUND","question":"The velocity of sound in air is 15\u2218C is 340 ms-1 at 47\u2218C","images":[],"options":{"A":"790ms-1","B":"602ms-1","C":"358ms-1","D":"322ms-1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The velocity of sound in air is directly proportional to the square root of absolute temperature (in kelvin)  V \u221d \u221aT  V=K\u221aT;K=VT  for two cases  V1\u221aT=V2\u221aT2  T1 = 15\u2218C = 15 + 273 = 288k  V1 = 340m/s  V2 = ?  T2 = 47\u2218C = 47 + 273 = 320k  340\u221a288=V2\u221a320  V2=320\u221a320\u221a288  V2 = 358m/s","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>23","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"Which of the current-voltage characteristics shown below is the exhibited by an ohmic conductor","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"","B":"","C":"","D":""},"answer":"B","explanation":"An ohmic conductor is a conductor which obeys ohm's law. The V-I graph for an ohmic conductor is a striaght ine passing through origin. Examples of ohmic conductors are metals . The V-I graphs for a non-ohmic conductors is a curve . examples are junction diode, electrolyte e.t.c","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>24","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : WORK DONE IN A GRAVITATIONAL FIELD","question":"A 500N box rests on a horizontal floor. A constant horizontal force is exerted on the box so that it moves through its 8m. If the coefficient of kinetic friction between the floor and the box is 0.22, calculate the work done on the box.","images":[],"options":{"A":"150J","B":"440J","C":"400J","D":"110J"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Distance moved, x = 8m  snce a constant force is applied then the force is equal t the frictional force , FR  FR = UR  Coefficient of friction, U =0.22  Nomal reaction , r = 200N  FR = 0.22 x 500   = 110N  Workdone , w = Force x distance, x  W = 880J","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>25","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"The diagram above illustrates a ball of mass m sliding down a plank inclined at an angle of \u03b8 to the horizontal.    The normal force on the ball is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"mgsin\u2205","B":"mgtan\u2205","C":"mgcos\u2205","D":"mgcot\u2205"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The normal reaction/force on a body on a horizontal surface is R = mg ; but that on a body on an inclined surface is R = mgCos\u03b8","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>26","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"EQUILIBRIUM OF FORCES : CONDITIONS FOR EQUILIBRIUM OF RIGID BODIES UNDER THE ACTION OF PARALLEL AND NON-PARALLEL FORCES","question":"The diagram above illustrates a ball of mass m sliding down a plank inclined at an angle of \u03b8 to the horizontal. The net force on the ball along the plank is","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"mgsin\u2205+F","B":"F-mgcos\u2205","C":"mgsin\u2205-F","D":"F+mgcos\u2205"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The force which tends to bring down a body on an inclined surface is mgsin\u2205. for the mass m on the plank , this is in opposite direction to the frictional force . Since the mass the mass slides down the inclined plank, the mgsin\u2205 is greater than the frictional force , F . Therefore the net force on the plank is mgsin\u2205 - F","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>27","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"SOUND WAVES : SOURCES OF SOUND","question":"What factors determines the frequency of a note emitted by a vibrating string?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Amplitude of vibration, force constant of string and length of string","B":"Amplitude of vibration, force constant of string and tension in string","C":"Mass per unit length of string, tension in string and length of string","D":"Force constant of string, tension in string and length of string"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The frequency of a note emitted by a vibrating string is given byF0=12l\u221aTU  Where F0 = Fundamental frequency , T = tension in the string, U = mass per unit lenght. therefore , the frequency depends on lenght , mass per unit lenght and tension.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>28","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CONCEPTS OF ELECTRIC FIELD, ELECTRIC FIELD INTENSITY (POTENTIAL GRADIENT) AND ELECTRIC POTENTIAL.","question":"The magnitude of the force experienced by a charge of 1.6 x 10-8c in a uniform electric field o intensity 5 x 10 5N/C is","images":[],"options":{"A":"3.2 x 10 -14N","B":"8.0 x 10 -3N","C":"8.0 x 10 3N","D":"3.1 x 10 13N"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Electricfieldintensity,E=force,Fcharge,q  q = 1.6 x10-8, E =5 x 105  5x105=F1.6 x 10-8  F = 0.008 = 8.0 x 10-3 N","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>29","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"MOTION : VISCOSITY (FRICTION IN FLUIDS)","question":"which of the following statement about viscosity is true? it","images":[],"options":{"A":"depends on areas of the surfaces in contact","B":"occurs in fluids","C":"is independent of the relative velocity of the layer","D":"depends on the tangential force between the layers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Viscosity is a property of fluids (both liquids and gases) that measures their resistance to flow. It is caused by the internal friction within the fluid, which is the result of the cohesive forces between its molecules. Therefore, the statement that viscosity occurs in fluids is true, making option 2 the correct answer.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>30","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"RECTILINEAR ACCELERATION : CONCEPT OF ACCELERATION/DECELERATION","question":"A motorcycle starting from rest, is uniformly accelerated such that its velocity in 10s is 72km/h-1, What is the acceleration?","images":[],"options":{"A":"108ms -2","B":"86ms -2","C":"4ms -2","D":"2ms -2"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Initial velocity , U = 0m/s  Finalvelocity,v=72khs-1=72km1hr=20ms  Time,t = 10s  Acceleration, a = ?  Recall, v = u + at  20 = 0 + a(10)  20 = 10a  20/10 = a  a = 2m/s2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>31","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : TEMPERATURE AND ITS MEASUREMENT","question":"The temperature of an object is raised by 120 \u2218C. The resulting increase in its absolute temperature is","images":[],"options":{"A":"50 K","B":"120 K","C":"200 K","D":"393 K"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A change in temperature in degree celsius has the same value as a change intemperature in kelvin , hence , 120\u2218C is the same as 120k.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>32","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION (S.H.M)","question":"Which of the following statement about the motion of a simple pendulum is true?","images":[],"options":{"A":"it is a simple harmonic motion when the angle of displacement is large","B":"it passes the equilibrium position with minimum speed","C":"it possesses maximum kinetic energy at the extreme position","D":"it swings faster at the poles than at the equator"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Option A is wrong in te sense that a large angle of displacement result to conical oscillation .   option B is wrong because the speed of a simple pendulum is maximum at equilibrum position,option c is also wrong because velocity is zero at the extreme position which makes the kinetic energy to be zero.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>33","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"MAGNETIC FIELD : MAGNETIC FORCE ON A MOVING CHARGED PARTICLE","question":"An electron of mass m and charge e curves in a circular path in a magnetic field of flux density B. How long does it take to complete one orbit?","images":[],"options":{"A":"2\u22bceBx","B":"2Bme\u22bc","C":"2\u22bcmBe","D":"Be2xm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The force, F on a charge q moving perpendicularly in a magnetic field of strenght B wth veocity V is given as F = qvB. Since the particles is an electron , then e is used instead of q.  F = eVB.  the centripetall force needed for the electron to move in its orbit is given asF=mv2vr  Where r is the radius of the orbit  since F = F  eVB = mV2/r  eB=mvr  For a complete orbit circumference of a circle (2\u22bcr) must hae been covered.  v=Distancetime   =2\u22bcrt  eBr=Nx2\u22bcrt  eB=2\u22bcBt  eBt = 2\u22bcm,  t=2\u22bcmBe","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>34","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : PHOTOELECTRIC EFFECT","question":"Which of the following about photoelectrons is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A faint green light produces photoelectrons with less kinetic energy than a bright red light","B":"A red light releases a smaller number of electrons than a green light","C":"A faint green light produces photoelectrons with greater kinetic energy than a bright red light","D":"A red light produces more photoelectrons than a green light"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The kinetic energy of photoelectrons is determined by the frequency (or color) of light, not its intensity (or brightness). Green light has a higher frequency than red light, so photoelectrons ejected by green light will have more kinetic energy than those ejected by red light, regardless of the brightness of the light. Therefore, a faint green light can produce photoelectrons with greater kinetic energy than a bright red light.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>35","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : LATENT HEAT","question":"The sketched graph above illustrates  the heating curve of a 0.02 kg of water. Determine the approximate value of the specific latent heat of vaporization of water.","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"2.25 x 10 6 j kg -1","B":"4.17 x 10 3  jkg -3","C":"2.00 x 10 3 j kg  -1","D":"1.00 x 10 3 j kg -1"},"answer":"A","explanation":"specific latent heat of vapourization is amount of heat energy needed to change 1kg of liquid to vapour without a change in temperature . The heat absorbed by the liquid at the beginning of vapourization is 8 x 103J and heat absorbed after the change of stage is 53 x 103J. therefore , the total heat energy needed to change the liquid completely to vapour is  Q = 53 x 103 - 8 x 103 J = 45 x 103J  Recall, Q = mlv  Where , lv =  specific latent heat of vapourization   l=Qm=45x1030.02=2.25x106Jkg-1","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>36","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"In the hydraulic press, the force F applied to the diameter d of the cylinder by","images":[],"options":{"A":"F \u03b1 d2","B":"F \u03b1 d","C":"F \u03b1 d-1","D":"F \u03b1 d-2"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Pressure,p=Force,fArea,A Since he area is circular, the A = \u22bcr2  P = F/\u22bcr2  Radius,r=Diameter,d2  r=d2  p=f\u22bc(d/2)2  p=F\u22bcd24  px\u22bcd24=F  F = (p\u22bc/4)d2  p\u22bc/4 is constant   F = kd2  F \u221dd2","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>37","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"SIMPLE A.C. CIRCUITS : REACTANCE AND IMPEDANCE","question":"In an electric circuit, an inductor of inductance 0.5 H and resistance 50 \u038f is connected to an alternating current source of frequency 60 Hz. Calculate the impedance of the circuit","images":[],"options":{"A":"50.0 \u038f","B":"150.0 \u038f","C":"195.0 \u038f","D":"1950.1 \u038f"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Inductance, l = 0.5H  Resistance , R = 50\u038f  Frequency, f = 60Hz  impedance , z = ?  Z = \u221aR2 + Xl  Where XL =inductive reactance  XL = 188.66\u038f  Z = \u221a502 + 188.62  Z = \u221a2500+3559.96  Z = \u221a3809.96  A = 195.1\u038f  Z = 195.0\u038f","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>38","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPTS OF MATTER : CONCEPTS OF MATTER","question":"Which of the following statement correctly explains why a total solar eclipse would be seen by people on only  small portion of the earth surface? The","images":[],"options":{"A":"moon is larger in diameter than the earth","B":"earth is larger in diameter than the sun","C":"earth revolves around the sun","D":"earth is a larger in diameter than the moon"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Solar eclipse occurs when the sun, moon and earth are collinear i.e in a straight line, with the moon at the middle , such that the moon cast it shadow on earth surface. The moon's shadow is narrow when it reaches the earth, so the region from which the eclipse is visible is small the earth is larger in diameter than the moon.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>39","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"PRODUCTION AND PROPAGATION OF WAVES : SPEED, FREQUENCY AND WAVELENGTH","question":"Water waves have a wavelength of 3.6cm and speed of 18cm s -1 in deep water. If the waves enters a shallow water with wave length of 2.0cm, calculate the speed of the waves in the shallow water.","images":[],"options":{"A":"0.4cm s -1","B":"2.5cm s -1","C":"10.0cm s -1","D":"10.8 m s -1"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Wavelenght in deep water, = 3.6cm  Speed in deep water, Vd = 18cm-1  Wavelenght in shallow water \u22cbs = 2.0cm  Speed in shallow water. Vs = ?  VdVs=\u22cbd\u22cbs  18Vs=3.2.0  18 x 2 = 3.6Vs  36 = 3.6Vs  363.6=Vs  Vs = 10.0cms-1","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>40","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : PRODUCTION OF ELECTRIC CURRENT","question":"An a.c generator can be converted to a d.c electric motor by replacing the","images":[],"options":{"A":"slip ring with a split ring, and connecting a battery","B":"split ring with slip rings and connecting a battery","C":"a.c with d.c source and connecting a battery","D":"a.c and d.c source and connecting split rings."},"answer":"A","explanation":"Slip rings are used in an ac generator while split rings are used in a dc generator. To convert an ac generator to a d.c generator , the slip are removed and replaced with split rings. Also, a.c generator uses concave magnets , these can be changed , then the coil is replaced with armature.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>41","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"A ray of light travels obliquely from a dense medium to a denser medium. Which of the following statement is true about the light?","images":[],"options":{"A":"The wavelength of the light increases in the second medium","B":"The speed of the light increases in the second medium","C":"The light refracts towards the normal","D":"There is a change in the  frequency of the light."},"answer":"C","explanation":"When a ray of light travels from a less then medium to a denser medim  - The refracted ray moves closer to th normal i.e the angle of refraction becomes smaller than the angle of incidence  - The speed of light decreases   -the wave lenght of the light decreases  - the frequency of the light is unaffected","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>42","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"WAVE-PARTICLE PARADOX : DUALITY OF MATTER","question":"The electron of mass 9.1 x 10 -31 kg is travelling at a speed of 2.0 x 10 6 ms -1. Calculate the associated  wavelength of the electron.(h=6.6 x 10 -34 js)","images":[],"options":{"A":"3.63 x 10 -10 m","B":"3.63 x 10 -8m","C":"3.63 x 10 -7m","D":"6.89 x 10 -4m"},"answer":"A","explanation":"ass , m =  9.1 x 10-31g  Speed, v = 2.0 x 106ms-1  Wave lenght , \u03bb = ?  Planck's constant, h = .6 x 10-34Js  From DeBroglie equation   \u03bb=hphere p = linear momentum   but , p = mv  \u03bb=hmv  \u03bb.x10-349.1 x 10-31 x 2 x 106  \u03bb = 3.3 x 10-10m","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>43","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : MELTING POINT","question":"Which of the following statements about the process of melting of a solid are true? The temperature of the solid will  i. Remain steady until melting starts  ii. Keep rising until melting  starts  iii. Remains steady as melting proceeds  iv. Keep rising as melting proceeds","images":[],"options":{"A":"I and III only","B":"III and IV only","C":"I,II and III only","D":"II, III, IV only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"During change of state , there is no change in temperature, for solid to change to liquid, heat must be supplied and as it starts rising again after melting has taken place. therefore, the temperature rises before melting takes place remains steady duirng melting and keeps rising after melting .","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>44","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"WORK, ENERGY AND POWER : WORK DONE IN A GRAVITATIONAL FIELD","question":"A diver steps off a diving platform that is 10m above the water. If there is no air resistance during the fall, there will be a decrease in the diver's","images":[],"options":{"A":"gravitational potential energy","B":"total mechanical energy","C":"kinectic energy","D":"momentum"},"answer":"A","explanation":"As he diver steps off the diving platform, since there is no air resistance, the divers falll with constant velociy , therefore it linear momentum and knetic energyremains constant, also , the divers total mechanical energy (sum of potential and kinetic) remains the same but the gravitational potential energy decreases due to decrease in height.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>45","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : COULOMB\u2019S LAW","question":"Which of the following action would increase the electric force between two positively charged particles?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Decreases the mass of the particles","B":"Decreases the distance between the particles","C":"increasing the distance between the particles","D":"increases the mass of the particles"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The force of attraction or repulsion between two charges is inversely proportional to the square of the distance between them.  F\u221d1d2;F=Kd2 where k is a constant . This implies that as the distance between he charged particles decreases, electric force increases and vice versa.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>46","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : SOURCES OF LIGHT","question":"A luminous objects is one that","images":[],"options":{"A":"gives off dim blue-green light only in the dark","B":"gives out light of its own","C":"shines by reflected light only","D":"glows only in the presence of light"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A luminous objects is an object which emit light on their own whole non luminous objects reflects light falling on them","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>47","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"FUNDAMENTAL AND DERIVED QUANTITIES AND UNITS : DERIVED QUANTITIES AND UNITS","question":"Which of the following units is not fundamental?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Metre","B":"Kilogram","C":"joule","D":"Candela"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fundamental units are units of fundamental quanlities and they are seven , kelvin, mole , candela, amperes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>48","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"HEAT ENERGY : HEAT TRANSFER","question":"The vacuum between the double walls of a thermos flask reduces heat loss through","images":[],"options":{"A":"conduction and radiation","B":"convection and conduction","C":"radiation only","D":"conduction only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The vaccum between the walls of a vacuum flask prevent heat being transferred from the inside to the outside by conduction since both conduction and convection require material medium for their transference.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>49","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"STRUCTURE OF THE ATOM : PHOTOELECTRIC EFFECT","question":"In photoelectric effect, the number of electrons emitted per seconds from a metallic surface is proportional to the","images":[],"options":{"A":"intensity of the incident radiation","B":"frequency of the incident radiation","C":"energy of the incident radiation","D":"work function of the metal"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The number of electrons emitted is proportional to the intensity or the brightness of the incident radioaction.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Physics>2020>50","subject":"Physics","year":"2020","type":"Objective","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"When two cells of negligible internal resistances and equal e.m.f denoted by E 1 and E 2 are connected in parallel, the combined e.m.f. E is given by","images":[],"options":{"A":"E= E 1 + E 2","B":"1E=1E1+1E2","C":"E = E 1 = E 2","D":"E=E1E2"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When cells are connected in series, the combined e.m.f is the sum of the e.m.f of each cell but when cells of eqaul e.m.f are connected in parallel the combined e.m.f is the same as the e.m.f of one of the cells. i.e E = E1 = E2.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];